collection element¶

Collection element is used to specify collection values.

Based on the context, in which collection element is used, it might use collectionType and itemType attributes to specify collection type and collection items type, or these values will be derived by IoC.Configuration.

Note

The possible values of collectionType attribute currently are enumerable, list, readOnlyList, and array.

For example, if collection is used to specified as a constructor parameter, or injected property value, collectionType and itemType attributes are required, along with the name attribute.

On the other hand, if collection is used to provide a return value in autoProperty or autoMethod elements, this attributes are not used, and IoC.Configuration determines the type of the collection from the auto-generated property or method return type.

Note

Refer to IoCConfiguration_collection.xml for more examples on collection element.

Example 1: Using collection element to specify constructed parameter value in service implementation¶

 1<services>
 2    <selfBoundService
 3        type="IoC.Configuration.Tests.Collection.Services.CollectionsTestClass1"
 4        scope="singleton" >
 5
 6        <parameters>
 7            <!--Demo of collection element used as a constructor parameter.-->
 8            <collection name="readOnlyListParam"
 9                        collectionType="readOnlyList"
10                        itemType="System.Int32">
11              <int32 value="17"/>
12              <int32 value="24"/>
13              <int32 value="27"/>
14            </collection>
15
16            <!--Demo of collection element used as a constructor parameter.-->
17            <collection name="arrayParam"
18                        collectionType="array"
19                        itemTypeRef="IInterface1">
20              <injectedObject typeRef="IInterface1"/>
21              <constructedValue typeRef="Interface1_Impl">
22                <parameters>
23                  <int32 name="param1" value="29"/>
24                </parameters>
25              </constructedValue>
26            </collection>
27        </parameters>
28    </selfBoundService>
29<services>

Example 2: Using collection element to specify injected property value¶

 1<services>
 2    <selfBoundService
 3        type="IoC.Configuration.Tests.Collection.Services.CollectionsTestClass1"
 4        scope="singleton" >
 5
 6        <injectedProperties>
 7            <!--Demo of collection element used to initialize
 8                the value of injected property.-->
 9            <collection name="EnumerableValues"
10                        collectionType="enumerable"
11                        itemType="SharedServices.Interfaces.IInterface1" >
12              <constructedValue typeRef="Interface1_Impl">
13                <parameters>
14                  <int32 name="param1" value="18"/>
15                </parameters>
16              </constructedValue>
17              <settingValue settingName="DefaultInterface1Value"/>
18              <injectedObject typeRef="IInterface1"/>
19            </collection>
20
21            <!--Demo of collection element used to initialize
22                the value of injected property.-->
23            <collection name="ListValues"
24                        collectionType="list"
25                        itemTypeRef="IInterface1">
26              <injectedObject typeRef="IInterface1"/>
27              <settingValue settingName="DefaultInterface1Value"/>
28              <constructedValue typeRef="Interface1_Impl">
29                <parameters>
30                  <int32 name="param1" value="139"/>
31                </parameters>
32              </constructedValue>
33            </collection>
34        </injectedProperties>
35    </selfBoundService>
36<services>

Example 3: Using collection element to specify a returned value for auto-generated method¶

 1<autoGeneratedServices>
 2    <!--Demo of collection element used in auto-implemented method and property
 3        return values.-->
 4    <autoService interface="IoC.Configuration.Tests.Collection.Services.IAutoService1">
 5        <autoMethod name="GetAllActionIds"
 6                    returnType="System.Collections.Generic.IReadOnlyList[System.Int32]">
 7            <methodSignature>
 8                <int32 paramName="appId"/>
 9            </methodSignature>
10            <if parameter1="3">
11                <collection>
12                    <int32 value="27"/>
13                    <int32 value="17"/>
14                </collection>
15            </if>
16            <default>
17              <collection>
18                <int32 value="13"/>
19                <int32 value="27"/>
20                <int32 value="17"/>
21              </collection>
22            </default>
23        </autoMethod>
24    </autoService>
25</autoGeneratedServices>

Example 4: Using collection element to provide a service implementation¶

 1<service type="System.Collections.Generic.IReadOnlyList[SharedServices.Interfaces.IDbConnection]">
 2    <valueImplementation scope="singleton">
 3        <collection>
 4            <settingValue settingName="DefaultDBConnection"/>
 5
 6            <constructedValue type="SharedServices.Implementations.SqlServerDbConnection">
 7                <parameters>
 8                    <string name="serverName" value="SQLSERVER2012"/>
 9                    <string name="databaseName" value="DB1"/>
10                    <string name="userName" value="user1"/>
11                    <string name="password" value="password123"/>
12                </parameters>
13            </constructedValue>
14
15            <constructedValue type="SharedServices.Implementations.SqlServerDbConnection">
16                <parameters>
17                    <string name="serverName" value="SQLSERVER2016"/>
18                    <string name="databaseName" value="DB2"/>
19                    <string name="userName" value="user2"/>
20                    <string name="password" value="password456"/>
21                </parameters>
22            </constructedValue>
23
24            <constructedValue type="TestPluginAssembly1.Implementations.MySqlDbConnection">
25                <parameters>
26                    <string name="connectionString" value="user=User1;password=123"/>
27                </parameters>
28            </constructedValue>
29        </collection>
30    </valueImplementation>
31</service>
